						<div class="postbody">I tried modifing the american switch with an european cable and it still didn't work (even the video comes out super noisy as opposed to an unmodified european switch... don't know why).
<br />
<br />I think it's pretty clear the problem is inside the RF modulator in the console but I really don't understand : Why the same modulator would work fine in america and won't work in europe ? There is absolutely no reason or does it have to do with other waves interfering with it which aren't present in america ? Even that doesn't make any sense - I believe the modulator is the exact same and uses the same frequencies as the one in the PAL consoles, the only difference is that a NTSC video signal is modulated instead of a PAL video signal.
<br />
<br />The only difference in the NES' side is that it is powered by 9V AC 50 Hz instead of 9V AC 60 Hz... would that make any difference ?
<br />
<br />Another explaination would that something inside the console would have been broken while it was shipped here, but it was obviously packaged with a lot of care with those bubbles everywhere I don't think any damage to the console could have been done.
<br />
<br />As I said above I can't take away the secure screws - I was able to remove one screw with pliers, but I still have 4 other screws which don't want to move - they even got pretty damaged and the most they are damaged the least chances I have to be able to eventually remove them  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_cry.gif" alt=":cry:" title="Crying or Very sad" /></div>

					
